GSTools: The Python toolbox for your geo-statistical project!¶

Sebastian Müller, Lennart Schüler, Alraune Zech, Sabine Attinger and Falk Heße¶

To navigate through the presentation, use the arrows in the lower right corner or your arrow-keys (right → next section; down → go through current section)

Motivation¶

Geo-scientific model development is lacking comprehensive open source tools, that provide state-of-the art geo-statistic methods. To bridge this gap, we developed a geo-statistical toolbox named GeoStatTools (GSTools), which is a Python package providing an abundance of methods in a modern easy-to-use approach.

Purpose¶

GeoStatTools provides geostatistical tools for various purposes:

  • random field generation
  • conditioned field generation
  • incompressible random vector field generation
  • simple and ordinary kriging
  • variogram estimation and fitting
  • many readily provided and even user-defined covariance models
  • plotting and exporting routines

Installation¶

You can install gstools via pip or conda:

pip install gstools  /  conda install gstools

Tutorial 1: Random Field Generation¶

The main feature of GSTools is the spatial random field generator SRF, which can generate random fields following a given covariance model. The generator provides a lot of nice features, which will be explained in the following.

GSTools generates spatial random fields with a given covariance model or a semi-variogram. This is done by using the so-called randomization method. The spatial random field is represented by a stochastic Fourier integral and its discretized modes are evaluated at random frequencies.

GSTools supports arbitrary and non-isotropic covariance models.

A Very Simple Example¶

We are going to start with a very simple example of a spatial random field with an isotropic Gaussian covariance model and following parameters:

  • variance $\sigma^2=1$
  • correlation length $\ell=10$

First, we set things up and create the axes for the field. We are going to need the SRF class for the actual generation of the spatial random field. But SRF also needs a covariance model and we will simply take the Gaussian model.

In [2]:
import gstools as gs

x = y = range(100)

Now we create the covariance model with the parameters $\sigma^2$ and $\ell$ and hand it over to SRF. By specifying a seed, we make sure to create reproducible results:

In [3]:
model = gs.Gaussian(dim=2, var=1, len_scale=10)
srf = gs.SRF(model, seed=20170519)

With these simple steps, everything is ready to create our first random field. We will create the field on a structured grid (as you might have guessed from the x and y), which makes it easier to plot.

In [4]:
field = srf.structured([x, y])
srf.plot()
Out[4]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fe2f6615e48>

Creating Fancier Fields¶

Only using Gaussian covariance fields gets boring. Now we are going to create much rougher random fields by using an exponential covariance model and we are going to make them anisotropic.

The code is very similar to the previous examples, but with a different covariance model class Exponential. As model parameters we a using following

  • variance $\sigma^2=1$
  • correlation lengths $\ell=(12, 3)$
  • rotation angle $\theta=\pi/8$
In [5]:
import numpy as np
x = y = np.arange(100)
model = gs.Exponential(dim=2, var=1, len_scale=[12.0, 3.0], angles=np.pi / 8)
srf = gs.SRF(model, seed=20170519)
srf.structured([x, y])
srf.plot()
Out[5]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fe2f4290240>

Tutorial 2: The Covariance Model¶

One of the core-features of GSTools is the powerful CovModel class, which allows you to define covariance models. The resulting models provide a lot of functionality and can be used for random field generation, variogram fitting and kriging.

A covariance model is used to characterize the semi-variogram, denoted by $\gamma$, of a spatial random field. In GSTools, we use the following formulation for an isotropic and stationary field:

$$\gamma\left(r\right)= \sigma^2\cdot\left(1-\mathrm{cor}\left(\frac{r}{\ell}\right)\right)+n$$

Where:

  • $\mathrm{cor}(h)$ is the normalized correlation function taking the non-dimensional distance $h=\frac{r}{\ell}$ (Rubin 2003)
  • $\sigma^2$ is the variance
  • $n$ is the nugget (subscale variance)
  • $\ell$ is the main length-scale

Provided Covariance Models¶

Here's an excerpt of the covariance models provided by GSTools:

Name Description $\mathrm{cor}(h)$
Gaussian The Gaussian covariance model $\exp\left(- \frac{\pi}{4} \cdot h^2\right)$
Exponential The Exponential covariance model. $\exp(-h)$
Matern The Matrn covariance model. $\frac{\left(\sqrt{\nu}\cdot h\right)^{\nu}}{2^{\nu-1}\cdot\Gamma\left(\nu\right)} \cdot \mathrm{K}_{\nu}\left(\sqrt{\nu}\cdot h\right)$
Stable The stable covariance model. $\exp(-h^{\alpha})$
Rational The rational quadratic covariance model. $\left(1 + \frac{h^2}{2\alpha}\right)^{-\alpha}$
Spherical The Spherical covariance model. $1-\frac{3}{2} h + \frac{1}{2} h^3 \; (h<1)$

Basic Methods¶

The covariance model class of GSTools provides the following basic methods:

  • CovModel.variogram: The variogram
  • CovModel.covariance: The (auto-)covariance
  • CovModel.correlation: The (auto-)correlation
In [6]:
model = gs.Exponential(dim=3, var=2.0, len_scale=10, nugget=0.5)
ax = model.plot("variogram")
model.plot("covariance", ax=ax)
model.plot("correlation", ax=ax)
Out[6]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fe2f42deda0>

Anisotropy and Rotation¶

In 2D and 3D you can specify rotation angles and anisotropy ratios to the CovModel. To explore the resulting spatial variogram, GSTools provides some convenient functions.

Note: The basic variogram methods given above always depend on the isotropified distances.

In [7]:
model = gs.Gaussian(dim=3, var=2.0, len_scale=[10, 5, 4], angles=2.5)
model.plot("vario_spatial")
print("Anisotropy representations:")
print("Anisotropy ratios:", model.anis)
print("Main length scale:", model.len_scale)
print("All length scales:", model.len_scale_vec)
print("Rotation angles:", model.angles)

Anisotropy ratios: [0.5 0.4]
Main length scale: 10
All length scales: [10.  5.  4.]

Spectral methods¶

The spectrum of a covariance model is given by:

$$S(\mathbf{k}) = \left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)^n \int C(\Vert\mathbf{r}\Vert) e^{i b\mathbf{k}\cdot\mathbf{r}} d^n\mathbf{r}$$

Since the covariance function $C(r)$ is radially symmetric, we can calculate this by the hankel-transformation:

$$S(k) = \left(\frac{1}{2\pi}\right)^n \cdot \frac{(2\pi)^{n/2}}{(bk)^{n/2-1}} \int_0^\infty r^{n/2-1} C(r) J_{n/2-1}(bkr) r dr$$

Where $k=\left\Vert\mathbf{k}\right\Vert$.

Depending on the spectrum, the spectral-density is defined by:

$$\tilde{S}(k) = \frac{S(k)}{\sigma^2}$$
In [8]:
#You can access these methods in the following way
model = gs.Gaussian(dim=3, var=2.0, len_scale=10)
ax = model.plot("spectrum")
model.plot("spectral_density", ax=ax)
Out[8]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fe2f13fdba8>

Different length scales¶

Besides the given length-scale, there are many other ways of characterizing a certain scale of a covariance model. We provide two common scales with the covariance model.

  • Integral scale: $$I = \int_0^\infty \rho(r) dr$$
  • Percentile scale: The distance, where the normalized variogram reaches a certain percentage of its (partial-)sill. This ignores the nugget.
In [9]:
model = gs.Stable(dim=3, var=2.0, len_scale=10)
per_scale = model.percentile_scale(0.9)
int_scale, len_scale = model.integral_scale, model.len_scale
print("90% Percentile scale:", per_scale)
print("Integral/Length scale:", (int_scale, len_scale))
ax = model.plot()
ax.axhline(1.8, color="k", label=r"90% percentile")
ax.axvline(per_scale, color="k", linestyle="--", label=r"90% percentile scale")
ax.axvline(int_scale, color="k", linestyle="-.", label=r"integral scale")
ax.axvline(len_scale, color="k", linestyle=":", label=r"length scale")
ax.legend()

90% Percentile scale: 17.437215135964117
Integral/Length scale: (9.027452929509336, 10)
Out[9]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7fe2f13af828>

Tutorial 3: Variogram Estimation¶

Estimating and fitting the spatial correlations is an important part of geostatistics. These spatial correlations can be expressed by the variogram, which can be estimated with the subpackage gstools.variogram. The variograms can be estimated on structured and unstructured grids.

Fit an estimated Variogram¶

Here we estimate the variogram of a synthetic field with an exponential model and eventually fit a stable model to it.

We use the following parameters:

  • dimension $d=2$
  • variance $\sigma^2=2$
  • correlation length $\ell=8$

Creation of the synthetic field¶

In [10]:
x = np.random.RandomState(19970221).rand(1000) * 100.0
y = np.random.RandomState(20011012).rand(1000) * 100.0
model = gs.Exponential(dim=2, var=2, len_scale=8)
srf = gs.SRF(model, mean=0, seed=19970221)
field = srf((x, y))
srf.plot()
Out[10]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fe2f1302c18>

Estimaton and fitting¶

In [11]:
# Estimate the variogram of the field with 40 bins.
bins = np.arange(40)
bin_center, gamma = gs.vario_estimate_unstructured((x, y), field, bins)
# Fit the variogram with a stable model (no nugget fitted).
fit_model = gs.Stable(dim=2)
fit_model.fit_variogram(bin_center, gamma, nugget=False)
ax = fit_model.plot(x_max=40)
ax.plot(bin_center, gamma, label="empirical variogram")
print(fit_model)

Stable(dim=2, var=1.9235070214339676, len_scale=8.151159627793442, nugget=0.0, anis=[1.], angles=[0.], alpha=1.0517946776379135)

Tutorial 4: Kriging¶

The subpackage gstools.krige provides routines for Gaussian process regression, also known as kriging. Kriging is a method of data interpolation based on predefined covariance models.

The aim of kriging is to derive the value of a field at some point $x_0$, when there are fixed observed values $z(x_1)\ldots z(x_n)$ at given points $x_i$.

The resluting value z_0 at x_0 is calculated as a weighted mean:

$$z_0 = \sum_{i=1}^n w_i \cdot z_i$$

The weights $W = (w_1,\ldots,w_n)$ depent on the given covariance model and the location of the target point.

The different kriging approaches provide different ways of calculating $W$.

Provided Kriging Methods¶

The following kriging methods are provided within the submodule gstools.krige.

Name Description Properties
Simple Simple kriging. Given mean.
Ordinary Ordinary kriging. Estimated mean.
Universal Universal kriging. Functional trend.
ExtDrift External drift kriging (EDK) Given trend.
Detrended Detrended simple kriging. Used for regression kriging.

Comparing simple and ordinary kriging¶

Here we demonstrate the differences between simple (given mean 1) and ordinary (estimated mean) kriging with a simple 1D example involving 5 conditional points:

cond_pos = [0.3, 1.9, 1.1, 3.3, 4.7]
cond_val = [0.47, 0.56, 0.74, 1.47, 1.74]
In [12]:
cond_pos = [0.3, 1.9, 1.1, 3.3, 4.7]
cond_val = [0.47, 0.56, 0.74, 1.47, 1.74]
In [13]:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
In [14]:
gridx = np.linspace(0.0, 15.0, 151)
model = gs.Gaussian(dim=1, var=0.5, len_scale=2)
kr1 = gs.krige.Simple(model=model, mean=1, cond_pos=cond_pos, cond_val=cond_val)
kr2 = gs.krige.Ordinary(model=model, cond_pos=cond_pos, cond_val=cond_val)
kr1(gridx)
kr2(gridx)
plt.plot(gridx, kr1.field, label="simple kriged field")
plt.plot(gridx, kr2.field, label="ordinary kriged field")
plt.scatter(cond_pos, cond_val, color="k", zorder=10, label="Conditions")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Universal kriging¶

Universal kriging is used to automatically estimate an internal regional drift, that is specified by a number of drift functions depending on the spatial positions.

In the following we will generate a kriging field involving a linear trend in 1D.

In [15]:
# synthetic condtions with a drift
drift_model = gs.Gaussian(dim=1, var=0.1, len_scale=2)
drift = gs.SRF(drift_model, seed=101)
cond_pos = np.linspace(0.1, 8, 10)
cond_val = drift(cond_pos) + cond_pos * 0.1 + 1
# resulting grid
gridx = np.linspace(0.0, 15.0, 151)
drift_field = drift(gridx) + gridx * 0.1 + 1
In [16]:
model = gs.Gaussian(dim=1, var=0.1, len_scale=2)
krig = gs.krige.Universal(model, cond_pos, cond_val, "linear")
krig(gridx)
ax = krig.plot()
ax.scatter(cond_pos, cond_val, color="k", zorder=10, label="Conditions")
ax.plot(gridx, gridx * 0.1 + 1, ":", label="linear drift")
ax.plot(gridx, drift_field, "--", label="original field")
ax.legend()
Out[16]:
<matplotlib.legend.Legend at 0x7fe2f15e0d68>

Tutorial 5: Conditioned Fields¶

Kriged fields tend to approach the field mean with increasing distance to observations. To generate random fields, that coincide with given observations, but are still random according to a given covariance model away from the observations proximity, we provide the generation of conditioned random fields.

The idea behind conditioned random fields builds up on kriging. First we generate a field with a kriging method, then we generate a random field, and finally we generate another kriged field to eliminate the error between the random field and the kriged field of the given observations.

To do so, you can choose between ordinary and simple kriging. In case of ordinary kriging, the mean of the SRF will be overwritten by the estimated mean.

Conditioning with Ordinary Kriging¶

Here we use ordinary kriging in 1D (for plotting reasons) with 5 given observations/conditions, to generate an ensemble of conditioned random fields. The estimated mean can be accessed by srf.mean.

In [17]:
# condtions
cond_pos = [0.3, 1.9, 1.1, 3.3, 4.7]
cond_val = [0.47, 0.56, 0.74, 1.47, 1.74]
gridx = np.linspace(0.0, 15.0, 151)
In [18]:
model = gs.Gaussian(dim=1, var=0.5, len_scale=2)
srf = gs.SRF(model)
srf.set_condition(cond_pos, cond_val, "ordinary")
fields = []
for i in range(100):
    # print(i) if i % 10 == 0 else None
    fields.append(srf(gridx, seed=i))
    label = "Conditioned ensemble" if i == 0 else None
    plt.plot(gridx, fields[i], color="k", alpha=0.1, label=label)
plt.plot(gridx, srf.krige_field, linestyle="dashed", label="kriged field")
plt.scatter(cond_pos, cond_val, color="k", zorder=10, label="Conditions")
plt.legend()
plt.show()

Tutorial 6: Field transformations¶

The generated fields of GSTools are ordinary Gaussian random fields. But there are several transformations to describe different real world problems in an appropriate manner.

GStools provides a submodule gstools.transform with a range of common transformations, including:

Name Description
binary Binary transformation.
discrete Discrete transformation.
boxcox Box-Cox transformation.
zinnharvey Zinn and Harvey transformation to connect low/high values.
normal_to_lognormal Transform to log-normal distribution.
normal_to_uniform Transform to uniform distribution on $[0, 1]$.

Example: Zinn & Harvey transformation¶

Here, we transform a field with the so called Zinn & Harvey transformation presented in Zinn & Harvey (2003). With this transformation, one could overcome the restriction that in ordinary Gaussian random fields the mean values are the ones being the most connected.

In [19]:
x = y = range(100)
model = gs.Gaussian(dim=2, var=1, len_scale=10)
srf = gs.SRF(model, seed=20170519)
srf.structured([x, y])
gs.transform.zinnharvey(srf, conn="high")
srf.plot()
Out[19]:
<matplotlib.axes._subplots.AxesSubplot at 0x7fe2f1723940>

Final words¶

This was a brief glimpse on what GSTools is capable of. The package is included in an infrastructure of Python packages called the "GeoStat Framework" (https://geostat-framework.org/), that provides multiple tools to analyze field measurements and run geo-statistical simulations.

Recently, the package PyKrige joined this framework and we are working on a sibling-like coexistence of both packages.

You can contact us via mail or on Gitter

Future¶

We are currently working on a publication for the v1.2.1 release.

There are a lot of feature requests, that we target to implement:

  • convenient geo-coordinate support
  • n-dimensional field generation and kriging
  • automated variogram estimation including anisotropy
  • adaptation to sklearn for machine learning support

We ar planing to cooperate with the developers of scikit-gstat, a similar package providing fancy variography routines, that is also presented at the EGU2020 (link)
